The paper presents a deep learning-based tool for protein identification from tandem mass spectrometry data. The paper involves the use of convolutional neural networks and recurrent neural networks, which are commonly used in computer vision and natural language processing, respectively. Therefore, it is likely to belong to the sub-categories of machine learning (cs.LG), computer vision (cs.CV), and artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The paper also involves the use of databases and graph assembly techniques, which are related to data management (cs.DB). Finally, the paper is focused on the application of protein identification in the context of human health and disease, which suggests a connection to bioinformatics (cs.BIO).
